Here's a simple JavaScript code snippet that demonstrates how to apply syntax highlighting colors to pre or code elements using CSS classes:

```javascript
// HTML structure for code block
<pre class="message-bubble">
  <code class="inline-code">console.log('Hello World!');</code>
</pre>

<style>
  .keyword {
    color: #fde68a;
  }
  .function {
    color: #fcd34d;
  }
  .string {
    color: #fed7aa;
  }
  .comment {
    color: #fdba74;
  }
</style>
```

This code snippet includes a basic HTML structure for a code block with an inline code element. The CSS styles define the colors for different syntax highlighting elements (keyword, function, string, and comment).

However, if you want to apply these colors dynamically using JavaScript, here's a more advanced example:

```javascript
// Get all code blocks on the page
const codeBlocks = document.querySelectorAll("pre.code");

codeBlocks.forEach((block) => {
  const codeText = block.innerText;
  const lines = codeText.split("\n");

  // Loop through each line and apply colors based on syntax highlighting rules
  lines.forEach((line, index) => {
    if (line.includes("console.")) { // Function call
      block.children[index].classList.add("function");
    } else if (line.startsWith("//")) { // Comment
      block.children[index].classList.add("comment");
    } else if (line.includes("'") || line.includes('"')) { // String literal
      block.children[index].classList.add("string");
    }
  });
});
```

This JavaScript code snippet loops through each code block on the page, parses the text content of each line, and applies the corresponding colors based on syntax highlighting rules.

Keep in mind that this is a basic example. You can enhance it by incorporating more advanced syntax highlighting rules, such as matching keywords or function names within strings.

